      "side": 1,
      "message": "Kind() returns TopKind unconditionally, whereas BuiltinValidator returns the parameter kind it validates. A consequence: a type mismatch like `#v \u0026 42` (with a string validator) isn\u0027t caught as a kind conflict — the validator claims to accept all kinds, so it runs and the decode fails with \"decoding value for validator: cannot use value 42 (type int) as string\". The message is informative, but it\u0027s an opaque decode error rather than a clean type conflict, and the validate function is invoked for wrong-typed values. Since T is known at construction, common scalar Go types could be mapped to their CUE kind (string→StringKind, int→IntKind, …) to get a proper kind gate; structs/slices could fall back to TopKind. Not necessarily for this CL, but worth a comment on why TopKind is the chosen behavior.",
      "revId": "e3bd7995717f120d7f99e4e7bef6f258f6c629a1",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    }
